article.headline: Taurasi's 21 points, 8 dimes pace Merc's rout
article.linkText: Phoenix gets first win over L.A. in 19 tries
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Rookie Diana Taurasi scored 21 points, helping
the Phoenix Mercury beat the best team in the WNBA and snap an
18-game losing streak against the Los Angeles Sparks.

Penny Taylor and Anna DeForge added 17 points apiece for Phoenix
in a 72-58 win over the Sparks on Wednesday night.

Taurasi added eight assists and six rebounds to lead the Mercury
to their fourth straight win and first against Los Angeles since
July 17, 1999.

"Look, anytime you can beat L.A., it's a huge win," Phoenix
coach Carrie Graf said. "They are such a talented team."

Lisa Leslie had 20 points and 14 rebounds -- her league-leading
16th double-double -- for the Sparks, who have the best record in
the WNBA (21-8).

Los Angeles, which had won 13 of 14 games, had its seven-game
winning streak snapped.

Phoenix (16-13) moved into a tie with Minnesota for third place
in the Western Conference, five games behind the first-place
Sparks.

"Even though I wasn't there for most of those losses, you still
feel them because you're a part of this team," Taurasi said.
"It's special."

The Sparks played without starting guard Tamecka Dixon, who
averages 9.6 points. She served a one-game suspension for shoving
Seattle's Betty Lennox in the face on Sept. 3.

The Mercury, winners of eight of nine, held the Sparks to 34.6
percent shooting. Los Angeles committed 19 turnovers.

"Obviously, the turnovers were a factor," Leslie said. "I
thought they shot the ball really well. They have a nice triple
threat out on the perimeter."

Taurasi scored 13 points, including eight during a 15-0 run, as
Phoenix took a 42-29 halftime lead. Los Angeles missed nine
straight shots and committed three turnovers during that 5-minute
span which ended with the Mercury leading by as many as 19 points.	   "We came out and dug ourselves a hole," Sparks coach Karleen
Thompson said. "Actually, it was more like a deep trench. They are
on a roll and they're trying to make the playoffs."

The Mercury didn't allowed the Sparks to get closer than eight
points in the second half.
